riests to take control","[string]It hid the body from the women","[string]It fulfilled Caesar\u0027s command","[string]Wine mixed with myrrh","[string]Water from the Jordan","[string]Bread from the temple","[string]Oil for anointing","[string]They cast lots for them","[string]They burned them","[string]They returned them to Mary","[string]They gave them to Barabbas","[string]Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James the younger and of Joses, and Salome","[string]Only Pilate\u0027s wife","[string]Martha and Mary of Bethany only","[string]No women were present","[string]A stone rolled against the entrance","[string]A wooden door","[string]A Roman seal only","[string]A curtain","[string]Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James, and Salome","[string]Peter, James, and John","[string]Pilate and the guards","[string]Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus","[string]The stone rolled away","[string]Jesus still lying there","[string]Roman guards asleep outside","[string]A sealed entrance","[string]Mary Magdalene","[string]Peter","[string]Salome","[string]Joseph of Arimathea","[string]Galilee","[string]Nazareth","[string]Jerusalem\u0027s temple","[string]Bethany","[string]A young man clothed in a white robe","[string]An armed soldier","[string]John the Baptist","[string]Elijah","[string]He has risen; he is not here","[string]He has gone back to Nazareth permanently","[string]He sleeps until the last day","[string]He was taken by the priests","[string]Their unbelief and hardness of heart","[string]Their lack of food","[string]Their poor fishing","[string]Their refusal to go to Nazareth","[string]The gospel to all creation","[string]Only the law of Moses","[string]The rebuilding of the temple","[string]Judgment on Rome alone","[string]They fled trembling and said nothing to anyone because they were afraid","[string]They immediately preached in the temple","[string]They ran to Pilate first","[string]They returned home rejoicing loudly","[string]Two disciples","[string]The chief priests","[string]Mary and Martha","[string]James and John alone","[string]Whoever believes and is baptized will be saved","[string]Only those from Galilee will be saved","[string]Belief is unnecessary if one is sincere","[string]Baptism saves apart from faith","[string]He was taken up into heaven and sat at God\u0027s right hand","[string]He returned to the tomb","[string]He hid in the wilderness","[string]He went to Rome","[string]It highlights restoration for the disciple who had denied Jesus","[string]It means Peter alone would see Jesus","[string]It excludes the other disciples","[string]It appoints Peter as a priest of the temple","[string]Even after the resurrection, faith must replace stubborn unbelief","[string]The resurrection changed nothing","[string]Only Mary could truly understand","[string]The disciples were rejected forever","[string]They accompany and confirm the preached gospel","[string]They replace the need for preaching","[string]They are for display only","[string]They are given to every person equally","[string]His exalted authority after resurrection","[string]His retirement from mission","[string]His defeat by earthly rulers","[string]His return to ordinary life","[string]Who will roll away the stone for us?","[string]Who will feed the crowd?","[string]Who will betray Jesus?","[string]Who will pay the tax?","[string]Seven demons","[string]A legion of demons","[string]Leprosy","[string]Blindness","[string]They did not believe","[string]They worshiped immediately","[string]They ran to Galilee at once","[string]They informed Pilate","[string]The Lord worked with them and confirmed the message","[string]They returned to fishing permanently","[string]Rome stopped all their preaching","[string]No one listened to them","[string]His holiness overcomes uncleanness rather than being defiled by it","[string]He ignores the law entirely","[string]He avoids all contact with suffering people","[string]He can help only after priestly approval","[string]John prepares the way, and Jesus immediately arrives as the promised Lord and stronger one","[string]John replaces Jesus as the main focus of the Gospel","[string]Jesus begins only after John\u0027s teaching is forgotten","[string]John and Jesus preach opposing messages","[string]It shows God\u0027s reign arriving in word and power against evil","[string]It proves Rome has already fallen","[string]It means teaching matters less than miracles","[string]It limits his mission to Capernaum only"]'::jsonb, 'The beginning of the gospel of Jesus Christ, the Son of God 40 days He went to a desolate place to pray Follow me, and I will make you become fishers of men You are my beloved Son; with you I am well pleased She served them He was moved with pity and touched him He is mightier than I; I am not worthy to stoop down and untie his sandals The Holy Spirit What is this? A new teaching with authority! That the kingdom of God has arrived in power, breaking the hold of both sickness and evil It signals to the reader Jesus''s true identity before the human characters understand it â€" a key Markan device The scribes appealed to tradition and precedent; Jesus spoke on his own authority â€" a claim that implied divine commission It creates urgency and rapid pacing, emphasizing the powerful breakthrough of God''s kingdom It echoes the new Eden â€" the second Adam reigns over creation as God intended, and angels serve him Jesus is the LORD (YHWH) of those prophecies; John is the Elijah-like forerunner of God''s own coming Jesus''s holiness is contagious â€" he does not become unclean by touching the unclean; he makes the unclean clean His power and mission were sustained by intimate communion with the Father â€" ministry flowed from prayer It is part of Mark''s Messianic Secret â€" supernatural beings know who Jesus is while humans remain blind Baptism through water (new Red Sea crossing), wilderness testing like Israel''s 40 years, then calling a new community â€" Jesus recapitulates and succeeds where Israel failed Mark emphasizes the deeds of the kingdom â€" what Jesus does reveals who he is â€" over extended teaching; the gospel is enacted, not only proclaimed Jesus as the new creation agent (Spirit hovering as at creation) and the Servant of the Lord (Isaiah''s beloved in whom God delights) A paralytic Levi To show the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins Jesus''s ministry brings a new reality that cannot be contained by old forms He forgives sins, calls sinners, reorients fasting, and claims lordship over the Sabbath A man with a withered hand Twelve Satan''s kingdom cannot stand if it is fighting itself It is the hardened attribution of God''s work in Jesus to an unclean spirit As hostility grows, Jesus forms the Twelve and defines family as those who do God''s will Good soil Peace, be still They are being given insight into the secret of the kingdom The kingdom grows by God''s power, and Jesus''s authority extends over creation itself Jesus has done what only God is portrayed as doing over the sea Legion Go home and tell what the Lord had done for him Faith clings to Jesus in both public desperation and hidden suffering He calls Jairus to trust his power beyond the finality of death He rules over demons, chronic uncleanness, and even death Nazareth Two by two Familiarity can harden people against recognizing Jesus rightly Jesus provides abundantly for the crowd like a shepherd for sheep without a shepherd Mission unfolds amid hostility, yet Jesus still shepherds and sustains his people What comes out of the heart Ephphatha Human tradition that can nullify God''s commandment Her humble persistence shows surprising faith from outside Israel The chapter moves from purity debates to mercy reaching Gentile territory and bodily restoration Seven You are the Christ Their influence is corrupting and marked by unbelief Peter accepts Jesus''s title but rejects the suffering path of the Messiah It moves from growing recognition of Jesus to the road of suffering and discipleship Moses and Elijah I believe; help my unbelief He is the beloved Son whose glory surpasses Moses and Elijah This kind requires dependent prayer rather than self-confidence The glorious Son still walks toward suffering and teaches humility, service, and radical holiness Son of David To sell what he had, give to the poor, and follow him Greatness is found in being servant of all He responds with clear-sighted faith while many insiders still misunderstand Jesus''s way Entering the kingdom requires humble reception and costly surrender rather than grasping control Hosanna It withered from the roots Judgment on fruitless religion linked with the temple scene God''s house is meant to be a house of prayer, not exploitation The messianic king enters Jerusalem, judges fruitless worship, and teaches trusting prayer He was killed and thrown out of the vineyard Hear, O Israel: the Lord our God, the Lord is one; love the Lord your God Israel''s leaders are rejecting God''s messengers and ultimately his beloved Son She gave out of her poverty with wholehearted trust Leaders seek status and reject the Son, while a poor widow gives herself wholly to God Not one stone would be left on another No one knows, not even the angels in heaven nor the Son, but only the Father To call disciples to endurance and vigilance To stress readiness because the master may return at any time Followers of Jesus must endure, discern, and stay awake without pretending to control the timetable A woman at Bethany A man carrying a jar of water He faces overwhelming anguish yet submits to the Father''s will It interprets Jesus''s approaching death as burial and devotion They misunderstand, sleep, flee, and deny, while Jesus remains faithful Barabbas The King of the Jews A Gentile observer recognizes something true about Jesus at the moment of his death Jesus''s death marks decisive access and judgment in relation to the temple order He is mocked as king yet truly reigns through suffering obedience Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James, and Salome Jesus has risen and is going before the disciples into Galilee It announces that the crucified Jesus has truly been raised It underscores the shocking, world-altering reality of the resurrection The risen Jesus goes ahead, and readers are left with the urgent question of faithful response A paralytic Levi The Sabbath Son, your sins are forgiven Sinners A physician New wine Plucking heads of grain To show the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins David ate the consecrated bread when he was in need They were amazed and glorified God The bridegroom is with them That he was blaspheming The Sabbath was made for man Jesus'' new work cannot simply be attached to the old system without tearing it Their inward reasoning He rose, took up his mat, and went out before them all Sitting at the tax office Jesus ate at Levi''s house with many tax collectors and sinners He would be taken away, and then they would fast A withered hand Twelve Beelzebul Those who do the will of God The Herodians Preach and cast out demons It cannot stand Blasphemy against the Holy Spirit To see whether he would heal on the Sabbath Is it lawful to do good or to do harm on the Sabbath? Boanerges, sons of thunder They were saying, ''He is out of his mind'' He must bind Satan before plundering his house Because Satan would be working against himself Obedience to God''s will creates true kinship with him Anger and grief at their hard hearts It was restored They fell down before him and cried out He strictly ordered them not to make him known Standing outside and calling for him The parable of the sower In a boat on the sea Peace, be still There was a great calm The word A lamp A mustard seed Teacher, don''t you care that we are perishing? It springs up quickly but withers because it has no root Cares of the world, deceitfulness of riches, and desires for other things The mystery of the Kingdom of God They were filled with great fear and asked who he was The measure you use will be measured to you, and more will be added God''s Kingdom grows in ways humans cannot fully explain They still had no faith He has authority over creation itself Thirty, sixty, and one hundredfold Hear Other little boats were with him In the stern on a cushion Legion Jairus Twelve years Do not fear, only believe Among the tombs They rushed into the sea and drowned She told him the whole truth Her faith About two thousand Leave their region Go home and tell what the Lord had done for him Who touched my clothes? He was oppressed by many demons To draw out her faith and restore her openly To speak of death as temporary before his power to raise her Jesus responds to both hidden uncleanness and public desperation with power and compassion Talitha cumi Peter, James, and John Give her something to eat They were overcome with great amazement Nazareth Two by two Five He walked on the water John the Baptist Authority over unclean spirits Two Gennesaret Isn''t this the carpenter, the son of Mary? Honor Because he heard of Jesus'' mighty works and feared John had risen Sheep without a shepherd Because John said Herod should not have his brother''s wife Take them away to a deserted place for rest Twelve They had not understood about the loaves and their hearts were hardened Shake off the dust under their feet People repented, many demons were cast out, and many sick were healed Take courage; it is I; do not be afraid They were made well Washing their hands before eating What comes out from the heart A Syrophoenician woman He was deaf and had a speech impediment Isaiah Evil thoughts and sinful acts She had an unclean spirit Ephphatha Corban Even the dogs under the table eat the children''s crumbs The child lying on the bed and the demon gone He has done all things well They were replacing it with human tradition Defilement is moral and spiritual, not based on ceremonial food distinctions It shows Gentile faith receiving Jesus'' mercy To deal personally and compassionately with him away from the crowd His ears and tongue They proclaimed it even more zealously Decapolis Honor your father and your mother Four thousand Seven Peter His cross A sign from heaven The yeast of the Pharisees and Herod Bethsaida He would suffer, be killed, and rise again Seven They thought he was talking about not having bread People like trees walking Get behind me, Satan Their demand showed unbelief despite what they had already seen The disciples'' understanding of Jesus is coming into focus gradually Do you not yet understand? Whoever loses his life for Jesus and the gospel will save it Caesarea Philippi Who do you say that I am? None The Son of Man will also be ashamed when he comes in glory Moses and Elijah This is my beloved Son. Listen to him He had a spirit that made him mute and threw him down Who was the greatest Peter, James, and John Three tents I believe; help my unbelief A little child They became dazzling white What they had seen on the mountain This kind comes out only through prayer Do not stop him He stands above the law and the prophets as the one the Father commands us to hear Because humble service to the lowly reflects receiving Jesus and the Father The radical seriousness of removing causes of sin The disciples'' rivalry and need for purity and peace What rising from the dead might mean Elijah He would be delivered, killed, and after three days rise Giving a cup of water in his name Marriage and divorce A rich man Bartimaeus The Kingdom of God He took them in his arms and blessed them The Kingdom of God James and John Son of David Your hardness of heart A camel through the eye of a needle Serve and give his life as a ransom for many He followed Jesus on the way God joined man and woman as one flesh from the beginning He had great possessions and would not leave them to follow Jesus Whoever would be great must be servant of all Salvation Sell what he had, give to the poor, and follow Jesus Mocking, flogging, death, and resurrection He threw off his cloak, sprang up, and came to Jesus A hundredfold now with persecutions, and in the age to come eternal life A colt A fig tree He drove out buyers and sellers It withered from the roots Hosanna A house of prayer for all nations A den of robbers By what authority do you do these things? The Lord has need of it Cloaks and leafy branches Rabbi, look! The fig tree you cursed has withered Forgive, if you have anything against anyone It exposed their refusal to answer truthfully and their fear of the crowd Judgment on fruitless religion Faith that does not doubt and trusts God in prayer Because they feared him as the crowd was astonished at his teaching The temple This mountain We do not know Neither will I tell you by what authority I do these things They killed him The things that are Caesar''s Sadducees Love the Lord your God with all your heart They were beaten, shamed, or killed Caesar''s Like angels in heaven Love your neighbor as yourself The stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone They knew neither the Scriptures nor the power of God To love God and neighbor How can the Christ be David''s son if David calls him Lord? To trap him in his words God is not God of the dead but of the living He understood the priority of loving God and neighbor They reject God''s messengers and even the beloved Son They wanted to arrest him but feared the crowd They heard him gladly They love honor and devour widows'' houses David called him Lord Not one stone would be left upon another Wars and rumors of wars All nations Watch Flee to the mountains Show signs and wonders to lead astray if possible Angels Recognize the season when signs appear The beginning of birth pains They would bear witness No one knows, not even the angels, nor the Son, but only the Father Coming in clouds with great power and glory Because deception would be a major danger before the end The Holy Spirit will give needed words in that hour For the sake of the elect Servants watching for their master''s return Peter, James, John, and Andrew Be saved Go down to take anything from the house What I say to you I say to all: Watch Judas Iscariot Costly ointment Gethsemane Three Passover Take; this is my body This is my blood of the covenant poured out for many With a kiss She had anointed his body beforehand for burial They would all fall away If possible, let this cup pass; yet not what I will, but what you will They slept Betrayal comes from one in close fellowship To explain the disciples'' failure to stay awake and pray That he would destroy the temple made with hands and build another not made with hands He was condemned for blasphemy He fled naked after leaving his linen cloth behind The fruit of the vine He broke down and wept I am Barabbas Simon of Cyrene The King of the Jews Joseph of Arimathea Are you the King of the Jews? Purple and a crown of thorns Darkness came over the whole land It was torn in two Because of envy Eloi, Eloi, lama sabachthani? Truly this man was the Son of God Place of a Skull The innocent Jesus is condemned while the guilty go free It signals a decisive opening and judgment connected to Jesus'' death They mockingly proclaim a truth they do not understand It provided an honorable burial and fixed the known location of Jesus'' tomb Wine mixed with myrrh They cast lots for them Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James the younger and of Joses, and Salome A stone rolled against the entrance Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James, and Salome The stone rolled away Mary Magdalene Galilee A young man clothed in a white robe He has risen; he is not here Their unbelief and hardness of heart The gospel to all creation They fled trembling and said nothing to anyone because they were afraid Two disciples Whoever believes and is baptized will be saved He was taken up into heaven and sat at God''s right hand It highlights restoration for the disciple who had denied Jesus Even after the resurrection, faith must replace stubborn unbelief They accompany and confirm the preached gospel His exalted authority after resurrection Who will roll away the stone for us? Seven demons They did not believe The Lord worked with them and confirmed the message His holiness overcomes uncleanness rather than being defiled by it John prepares the way, and Jesus immediately arrives as the promised Lord and stronger one It shows God''s reign arriving in word and power against evil', 'Mark 1:1 opens "The beginning of the gospel of Jesus Christ, the Son of God." Jesus was in the wilderness 40 days being tempted by Satan (Mark 1:13). "And rising very early in the morningâ€¦ he went out to a desolate place, and there he prayed" (Mark 1:35). "Follow me, and I will make you become fishers of men" (Mark 1:17). "A voice came from heaven, You are my beloved Son; with you I am well pleased" (Mark 1:11). "She began to serve them" (Mark 1:31). "Moved with pity, he stretched out his hand and touched him" (Mark 1:41). Mark 1:7: "After me comes he who is mightier than I, the strap of whose sandals I am not worthy to stoop down and untie." "He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit" (Mark 1:8). "What is this? A new teaching with authority! He commands even the unclean spirits, and they obey him" (Mark 1:27). Jesus''s comprehensive healing demonstrates that the kingdom of God has come to reverse all effects of the Fall. Mark uses dramatic irony: the reader knows who Jesus is (1:1; 1:11) long before the disciples confess it (8:29). "I say to you" (not "thus says the Lord") reflects Jesus speaking with inherent authority â€" a stunning contrast to rabbinic method. Euthys appears ~41 times in Mark, driving the action forward; the kingdom is bursting into history with force. The wilderness + wild animals + angelic service echoes Isaiah 11:6â€"9 and Psalm 91:11â€"13 â€" the new Adam restoring creation order. In Malachi 3:1 the Lord comes to his temple; John prepares the way for Jesus = Jesus is YHWH arriving in person. Unlike the OT purity system (defilement spreads outward), Jesus''s power spreads inward: holiness overcomes uncleanness. Even after enormous success (1:32â€"34), Jesus withdrew to pray; his authority came from the Father, not his own power. Demons see through the flesh; people do not. This irony runs through Mark, where the wrong beings keep revealing the secret. Mark 1 is a compressed new Exodus: the Spirit''s descent parallels the pillar of cloud, the wilderness echoes Numbers, and the calling mirrors Sinai. Mark''s structure foregrounds the inbreaking kingdom through action; proclamation and deed are inseparable, but deed is the lens. The Spirit hovering echoes Gen. 1:2 (new creation); "belovedâ€¦ well pleased" echoes Isa. 42:1 (Servant); both identities shape Mark''s Christology. Mark 2:3-4 describes a paralytic being lowered through the roof to Jesus. Mark 2:14 says Jesus called Levi from the tax office. Mark 2:10-12 links the healing with Jesus''s authority to forgive sins. Mark 2:18-22 uses bridegroom, patch, and wineskins imagery to show the newness of Jesus''s ministry. Mark 2 moves from forgiving the paralytic to declaring the Son of Man Lord even of the Sabbath. Mark 3:1-5 records Jesus healing a man with a withered hand. Mark 3:13-19 says Jesus appointed twelve. Mark 3:23-27 answers the Beelzebul accusation by showing a divided kingdom cannot stand. Mark 3:28-30 gives the warning in response to scribes saying Jesus had an unclean spirit. Mark 3 combines plots against Jesus, the appointing of the Twelve, and the redefinition of family. Mark 4:8 and 4:20 say the seed on good soil bore fruit. Mark 4:39 says Jesus rebuked the wind and said to the sea, ''Peace, be still!'' Mark 4:10-12 says the disciples are given the secret of the kingdom of God. Mark 4 moves from kingdom parables about growth to a demonstration of Jesus''s authority over the sea. Mark 4:41 shows the disciples stunned that even wind and sea obey Jesus. Mark 5:9 says the demons answered, ''My name is Legion, for we are many.'' Mark 5:19 says Jesus sent him home to tell what the Lord had done. Mark 5:21-43 interweaves the two stories around trusting Jesus. Mark 5:35-36 turns the crisis of death into a summons to faith. Mark 5 moves from Legion to the bleeding woman to Jairus''s daughter, showing sweeping authority. Mark 6:1-6 describes Jesus being rejected in Nazareth. Mark 6:7 says Jesus sent them out two by two. Mark 6:3-6 shows Nazareth stumbling over Jesus''s ordinary background. Mark 6:34-44 highlights Jesus''s compassion and miraculous provision. Mark 6 places the apostles'' mission and John''s martyrdom alongside Jesus''s compassionate feeding and sea crossing. Mark 7:20-23 says what comes out of a person defiles him. Mark 7:34 records Jesus saying ''Ephphatha,'' meaning ''Be opened.'' Mark 7:8-13 criticizes traditions that set aside God''s word. Mark 7:24-30 highlights her humble and trusting reply. Mark 7 joins inner purity teaching with Gentile faith and the healing of the deaf man. Mark 8:8 says seven baskets of leftovers were taken up. Mark 8:29 records Peter saying, ''You are the Christ.'' Mark 8:15 warns against the leaven of the Pharisees and Herod. Mark 8:29-33 shows Peter confessing Jesus yet resisting the prediction of suffering. Mark 8 centers on Peter''s confession, Jesus''s passion prediction, and the call to take up the cross. Mark 9:4 says Moses and Elijah appeared with Jesus. Mark 9:24 records the father''s cry. Mark 9:7 centers on the heavenly voice: ''This is my beloved Son. Listen to him.'' Mark 9:28-29 explains that this kind comes out by prayer. Mark 9 moves from the transfiguration to a passion prediction and teachings on humility and stumbling. Mark 10:47 says Bartimaeus cried out, ''Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!'' Mark 10:21 gives Jesus''s call to the rich man. Mark 10:43-45 says whoever wants to be great must be servant. Mark 10:46-52 ends with Bartimaeus receiving sight and following Jesus on the way. Mark 10 repeatedly opposes status, possession, and domination with childlike reception and servant discipleship. Mark 11:9-10 records the crowd crying, ''Hosanna!'' Mark 11:20 says the fig tree had withered from the roots. Mark 11 frames the temple cleansing with the fig tree episode, tying fruitlessness to judgment. Mark 11:15-17 says Jesus condemned turning the house of prayer into a den of robbers. Mark 11 joins the entry, temple action, fig tree, and teaching on prayer and forgiveness. Mark 12:8 says the tenants killed the son and cast him out. Mark 12:29-30 gives the first commandment in response to the scribe. Mark 12:1-12 exposes the leaders through the parable. Mark 12:41-44 says she gave more than the others because she gave all she had. Mark 12 moves from hostile leaders to the widow''s humble offering as a living contrast. Mark 13:2 foretells that not one stone would be left on another. Mark 13:32 says only the Father knows the day or hour. Mark 13 repeatedly urges watchfulness and endurance amid turmoil. Mark 13:34-37 uses the doorkeeper image to command watchfulness. Mark 13 combines suffering, proclamation, and vigilance without date-setting. Mark 14:3 describes a woman anointing Jesus at Bethany. Mark 14:13 says the disciples would meet a man carrying a jar of water. Mark 14:32-36 shows Jesus deeply distressed yet obedient in prayer. Mark 14:8 says the woman anointed Jesus beforehand for burial. Mark 14 contrasts Jesus''s obedience with the disciples'' weakness at multiple points. Mark 15:6-15 says Pilate released Barabbas instead of Jesus. Mark 15:26 says the inscription was ''The King of the Jews.'' Mark 15:39 records the centurion saying, ''Truly this man was the Son of God.'' Mark 15:38 says the veil of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom. Mark 15 saturates the passion with kingly language while showing Jesus enthroned through the cross. Mark 16:1 names the women who went to the tomb. Mark 16:6-7 announces the resurrection and the meeting in Galilee. Mark 16:6 says plainly, ''He has risen. He is not here.'' Mark 16:8 emphasizes trembling and astonishment at the empty tomb. Mark 16 leaves the reader facing the resurrection announcement and the call to respond in faith. In Mark 2, friends lowered a paralyzed man through the roof so Jesus could heal him. Jesus called Levi while he was sitting at the tax office. Jesus declared that the Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath. Jesus first announced forgiveness before commanding the paralytic to rise. Jesus said he came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance. Jesus said those who are sick need a physician, not those who are healthy. Jesus taught that new wine must be put into new wineskins. Jesus'' disciples were plucking grain on the Sabbath, which led to questions from the Pharisees. Jesus healed the paralytic as visible proof of his authority to forgive sins. Jesus referred to David eating the bread of the Presence when he and his companions were hungry. The crowd was amazed and glorified God, saying they had never seen anything like it. Jesus said wedding guests do not fast while the bridegroom is with them. The scribes reasoned that only God can forgive sins, so they viewed Jesus'' words as blasphemy. Jesus taught that the Sabbath serves human good, not the other way around. The image of unshrunk cloth shows the incompatibility of merely patching Jesus'' new work onto the old order. Jesus perceived in his spirit what the scribes were reasoning within themselves. The man immediately rose, picked up his mat, and walked out in front of everyone. Levi was seated at the tax office when Jesus said, ''Follow me.'' Levi hosted a meal where many tax collectors and sinners were reclining with Jesus. Jesus pointed ahead to his departure, saying then his disciples would fast. Jesus healed a man with a withered hand in the synagogue. Jesus appointed twelve to be with him and to be sent out to preach. The scribes accused Jesus of casting out demons by Beelzebul. Jesus said whoever does the will of God is his brother, sister, and mother. The Pharisees immediately conspired with the Herodians about destroying Jesus. Jesus appointed the twelve to preach and to have authority over demons. Jesus answered the accusation against him by saying a divided kingdom cannot stand. Jesus warned that blasphemy against the Holy Spirit never has forgiveness. They watched Jesus to find grounds to accuse him if he healed on the Sabbath. Jesus confronted their hardness by asking whether it was lawful to do good or to save life on the Sabbath. Jesus surnamed James and John Boanerges, meaning sons of thunder. Jesus'' relatives went out to seize him because people were saying he was beside himself. Jesus used the picture of binding the strong man to explain his power over Satan''s kingdom. Jesus argued that if Satan casts out Satan, his kingdom is divided and cannot stand. Jesus teaches that spiritual kinship is defined by doing God''s will. Mark notes that Jesus looked around with anger, grieved at their hardness of heart. When the man stretched out his hand, it was restored. The unclean spirits fell down before Jesus and cried out that he was the Son of God. Jesus repeatedly warned the spirits not to reveal him publicly. His mother and brothers stood outside and sent word, calling for him. Mark 4 opens with Jesus teaching the parable of the sower by the sea. Because of the crowd, Jesus taught from a boat while the people stood on the shore. Jesus rebuked the wind and said to the sea, ''Peace, be still.'' After Jesus spoke, the wind ceased and there was a great calm. Jesus explained that the sower sows the word. Jesus asked whether a lamp is brought to be put under a basket or under a bed. Jesus compared the Kingdom to a mustard seed that grows large. The frightened disciples woke Jesus with that desperate question. The rocky-ground hearers receive the word quickly but fall away when trouble comes. Jesus said these things choke the word so it becomes unfruitful. Jesus said the mystery of the Kingdom had been given to them, while outsiders heard in parables. The miracle left them in awe, wondering who Jesus was that even wind and sea obeyed him. Jesus warned his listeners to take heed how they hear, because response affects further understanding. The man sleeps and rises while the seed grows, showing the mysterious growth of the Kingdom. Jesus asked why they were afraid and whether they still had no faith. By commanding the wind and sea, Jesus demonstrates divine authority over creation. The good soil hears the word and bears fruit in increasing abundance. Jesus repeatedly says, ''Whoever has ears to hear, let him hear.'' Mark notes that other little boats were with Jesus as they set out across the sea. Jesus was asleep in the stern on a cushion while the storm raged. The demon answered, ''My name is Legion, for we are many.'' Jairus, a synagogue ruler, begged Jesus to come heal his little daughter. The woman had suffered from a flow of blood for twelve years. Jesus urged Jairus to trust him even after hearing that the girl had died. The man lived among the tombs and could not be restrained with chains. The herd rushed down the steep bank into the sea and drowned. When Jesus called her out, the woman came in fear and told him the whole truth. Jesus said, ''Daughter, your faith has made you well.'' Mark notes that the herd numbered about two thousand. The people were afraid and begged Jesus to depart from their region. Jesus sent the healed man back to his own people to testify about mercy received. Jesus perceived power had gone out from him and asked who had touched his garments. The name ''Legion'' indicates a multitude of demons rather than a single spirit. Jesus brought her forward so her faith would be named and her restoration would be public and personal. Jesus used sleep language to show that her death was not beyond his authority. The intertwined stories show Jesus meeting both a desperate ruler and a suffering outcast with equal authority and mercy. Jesus took the girl by the hand and said, ''Talitha cumi,'' meaning, ''Little girl, arise.'' Jesus allowed only Peter, James, and John to accompany him inside. After raising the girl, Jesus told them to give her something to eat. Those present were utterly astonished when the girl got up and walked. Jesus was rejected in his hometown of Nazareth. Jesus sent the twelve out two by two with authority over unclean spirits. Jesus fed the crowd with five loaves and two fish. Jesus came to the disciples walking on the sea. Herod ordered the beheading of John the Baptist. Jesus gave the twelve authority over unclean spirits as they went out. The disciples had five loaves and two fish. After crossing over, Jesus healed many in Gennesaret. The people stumbled over Jesus because they knew his ordinary family background. Jesus said a prophet is not without honor except in his hometown and among his relatives. Herod heard reports about Jesus and thought John had risen from the dead. Jesus had compassion on the crowd because they were like sheep without a shepherd. John condemned Herod''s unlawful marriage to Herodias, leading to his imprisonment. Jesus called the disciples to come away and rest because they had no leisure even to eat. After the five thousand were fed, twelve baskets full of broken pieces were collected. Mark connects their amazement to their failure to understand the feeding miracle. Jesus told them to shake off the dust as a testimony when they were rejected. The twelve preached repentance, cast out many demons, and healed many sick people. Jesus spoke comfort to the disciples when they were terrified on the sea. Everyone who touched the fringe of Jesus'' garment was made well. The Pharisees objected that the disciples ate with unwashed hands. Jesus taught that what comes from within, out of the heart, is what defiles a person. A Gentile Syrophoenician woman begged Jesus to cast the demon out of her daughter. Jesus healed a man who was deaf and spoke with difficulty. Jesus quoted Isaiah in rebuking hypocritical worship based on human tradition. Jesus listed evil thoughts, theft, murder, adultery, and other sins as coming from within. The woman''s little daughter had an unclean spirit, and she begged Jesus to cast it out. Jesus said ''Ephphatha,'' meaning ''Be opened.'' Jesus rebuked the practice of declaring resources ''Corban'' so they could not be used to honor parents. Her humble reply displayed faith, and Jesus granted her request. She found her daughter healed, lying on the bed, with the demon departed. The crowd marveled, saying Jesus had done all things well. Jesus said their traditions nullified God''s command, especially in the matter of honoring parents. Mark highlights Jesus'' teaching that uncleanness comes from the heart, not from food entering the body. The episode shows Jesus responding to faith outside Israel''s boundaries. Jesus'' private actions show personal care and direct attention to the man''s need. Jesus put his fingers into the man''s ears and touched his tongue. The more Jesus charged them to be quiet, the more widely they proclaimed it. The healing took place in the region of Decapolis. Jesus said their tradition undermined the command to honor father and mother. Jesus fed a crowd of about four thousand in Mark 8. Jesus used seven loaves to feed the four thousand. At Caesarea Philippi, Peter confessed that Jesus is the Christ. Jesus said anyone who would follow him must deny himself and take up his cross. The Pharisees demanded a sign from heaven to test Jesus. Jesus warned the disciples against the yeast of the Pharisees and Herod. Jesus healed a blind man at Bethsaida in a two-stage process. Jesus began to teach openly about his suffering, death, and resurrection. After the four thousand ate, seven baskets of broken pieces were collected. The disciples assumed Jesus was speaking about literal bread because they had forgotten to bring enough. After the first touch, the man said he saw people, but they looked like trees walking. Jesus strongly rebuked Peter for setting his mind on human things rather than God''s. Jesus'' deep sigh reflects grief at hardened unbelief that still demanded another sign. Placed next to Peter''s confession and misunderstanding, the staged healing mirrors partial spiritual sight becoming clearer. Jesus asked pointed questions to expose their slowness in grasping the significance of the miracles. Jesus teaches that true life is found through self-denial and loyalty to him. Peter''s confession came at Caesarea Philippi. Jesus asked the disciples directly who they said he was. Jesus asked what profit there is in gaining the whole world while forfeiting one''s soul. Jesus warned of future judgment for those ashamed of him in an adulterous and sinful generation. Moses and Elijah appeared with Jesus on the mountain. The heavenly voice identified Jesus as God''s beloved Son and commanded the disciples to listen to him. A father brought his son who was tormented by a destructive spirit. The disciples argued among themselves about who was the greatest. Jesus took Peter, James, and John up the high mountain. Peter suggested making three tents for Jesus, Moses, and Elijah. The father confessed both faith and weakness when asking Jesus to help his son. Jesus used a child to teach the disciples about humility and receiving the lowly. Jesus'' clothes became intensely white, beyond what any launderer could achieve. Jesus told them to tell no one what they had seen until the Son of Man had risen. Jesus said the disciples'' failure showed the need for dependence expressed in prayer. Jesus said the one doing mighty works in his name should not be forbidden. Moses and Elijah appear with Jesus, but the Father''s voice singles Jesus out as the one to hear. Jesus connects receiving the child with receiving him and the One who sent him. Jesus uses severe imagery to stress the urgency of dealing decisively with sin. After correcting their pride and exclusiveness, Jesus calls them to inner integrity and peace with one another. They kept the matter to themselves, questioning what rising from the dead meant. The disciples asked why the scribes said Elijah must come first. Jesus again predicted his betrayal, death, and resurrection. Jesus said even giving a cup of water to one who belongs to Christ would be rewarded. Mark 10 opens with Jesus teaching about marriage and divorce. A wealthy man came running to ask Jesus about inheriting eternal life. Jesus healed blind Bartimaeus as he was leaving Jericho. Jesus said whoever does not receive the Kingdom of God like a child shall not enter it. Jesus welcomed the children, took them in his arms, and blessed them. Jesus said how difficult it is for those who have wealth to enter the Kingdom of God. James and John asked to sit at Jesus'' right and left in his glory. Bartimaeus cried out, ''Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!'' Jesus said Moses wrote that command because of hardness of heart. Jesus said it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich person to enter God''s Kingdom. Jesus defined his mission in terms of service and sacrificial ransom. After receiving sight, Bartimaeus followed Jesus on the road. Jesus appealed to Genesis to ground marriage in God''s creation design. The man''s wealth exposed the competing loyalty of his heart. Jesus contrasted Gentile rule with Kingdom greatness expressed in humble service. When the disciples asked who can be saved, Jesus answered that with God all things are possible. Jesus called the man to radical discipleship by surrendering his possessions and following him. Jesus again predicted his coming suffering, death, and resurrection. Bartimaeus responded eagerly, throwing aside his cloak and coming to Jesus. Jesus promised multiplied blessing, persecution in this age, and eternal life in the age to come. Jesus entered Jerusalem riding on a colt. Jesus cursed a fig tree that had leaves but no fruit. Jesus cleansed the temple by driving out those buying and selling. The disciples saw that the fig tree had withered from the roots. The crowd shouted ''Hosanna'' as Jesus entered Jerusalem. Jesus said the temple should be a house of prayer for all nations. Jesus accused the temple merchants of turning it into a den of robbers. The chief priests, scribes, and elders questioned Jesus'' authority. Jesus instructed the disciples to say, ''The Lord has need of it.'' The crowd spread cloaks and branches on the road before Jesus. Peter pointed out the withered fig tree to Jesus. Jesus linked forgiving others with standing in prayer before the Father. Jesus used John''s baptism to reveal the leaders'' dishonesty and fear of public opinion. The cursing and withering of the fig tree functions as a sign of judgment on outward appearance without fruit. Jesus taught about bold, trusting prayer and not doubting in the heart. The leaders feared Jesus because the crowd was amazed at his teaching and authority. After entering Jerusalem, Jesus looked around at everything in the temple and then went out to Bethany. Jesus said that if one believes, he may say to this mountain, ''Be taken up and cast into the sea.'' Refusing to commit themselves, the leaders answered, ''We do not know.'' Because they would not answer honestly, Jesus declined to answer their question directly. In the parable, the tenants killed the beloved son after casting him out. Jesus told his questioners to render to Caesar what belongs to Caesar. The Sadducees, who say there is no resurrection, challenged Jesus in Mark 12. Jesus said the first commandment is wholehearted love for God. The tenants abused the owner''s servants one after another. Jesus asked whose image and inscription were on the denarius, and the answer was Caesar''s. Jesus said that in the resurrection people neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven. Jesus said the second commandment is to love your neighbor as yourself. Jesus quoted the rejected-stone text to interpret the parable and his own rejection. Jesus corrected the Sadducees by exposing their ignorance of both Scripture and God''s power. The scribe agreed that loving God and neighbor is more than all burnt offerings and sacrifices. Jesus asked how the Messiah can be merely David''s son when David calls him Lord. The question about tribute was designed to catch Jesus between popular resentment and Roman authority. Jesus used God''s words to Moses to show that the patriarchs live before God. The scribe grasped the heart of the law, showing nearness to the Kingdom. The parable exposes the leaders'' pattern of rejecting God''s servants and his Son. The leaders understood the parable was about them but held back because they feared the crowd. Mark notes that the common people heard Jesus gladly. Jesus warned against the scribes'' love of status and their exploitation of widows. Jesus emphasized that David himself called the Messiah ''Lord.'' Jesus foretold the destruction of the temple. Jesus warned of wars and rumors of wars as part of the coming troubles. Jesus said the gospel must first be preached to all nations. Jesus repeatedly commands his followers to watch. Jesus warned those in Judea to flee immediately when that sign appears. Jesus warned of deceptive signs and wonders from false christs and prophets. Jesus said the angels will gather the elect from the ends of the earth and heaven. The fig tree teaches discernment about nearness when its branch becomes tender and puts out leaves. Jesus described those early troubles as the beginning of birth pains, not the end itself. Jesus said persecutions would become opportunities to bear witness before rulers. Jesus stressed that the exact day and hour are unknown except to the Father. Jesus said the Son of Man will come in clouds with great power and glory. Jesus begins the discourse by warning against spiritual deception from false claimants and false prophets. Jesus encouraged trust in the Spirit''s help when disciples are brought before authorities. Jesus said those days would be shortened for the sake of the elect whom God chose. Jesus ends with the picture of servants staying awake for the return of their master. These four disciples asked Jesus privately when the temple destruction would happen. Jesus promised salvation to the one who endures to the end. Jesus stressed urgent flight without delay or retrieval of possessions. Jesus broadened the warning from the four disciples to all who follow him. Judas went to the chief priests to betray Jesus. A woman anointed Jesus with very costly ointment. Jesus prayed in Gethsemane before his arrest. Peter denied Jesus three times before the rooster crowed twice. Jesus shared the Passover meal with his disciples. Jesus identified the bread with his body. Jesus identified the cup with his covenant blood poured out for many. Judas used a kiss as the agreed sign to identify Jesus. Jesus said the woman had done a beautiful thing by preparing his body for burial. Jesus predicted that all the disciples would fall away that night. Jesus prayed honestly about the coming suffering while submitting to the Father''s will. Jesus found Peter, James, and John sleeping instead of watching with him. Jesus emphasized the pain and treachery of betrayal by one sharing the meal with him. Jesus used the saying to expose the disciples'' weakness in the face of temptation. Witnesses twisted Jesus'' words into a charge about destroying and rebuilding the temple. After Jesus affirmed his identity and spoke of the Son of Man, the high priest tore his garments and the council condemned him. Mark uniquely notes that a young man escaped naked after the crowd seized his linen garment. Jesus said he would not drink again of the fruit of the vine until the Kingdom. When Peter remembered Jesus'' words, he broke down and wept. Jesus answered directly, ''I am,'' and spoke of the Son of Man seated at the right hand of Power. The crowd asked for Barabbas to be released instead of Jesus. Simon of Cyrene was compelled to carry Jesus'' cross. The inscription over Jesus read, ''The King of the Jews.'' Joseph of Arimathea took courage, asked for Jesus'' body, and buried him. Pilate questioned Jesus by asking if he was the King of the Jews. The soldiers clothed Jesus in purple and crowned him with thorns to mock him. Darkness covered the whole land from the sixth hour until the ninth hour. At Jesus'' death the veil of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom. Pilate perceived that the chief priests had handed Jesus over out of envy. Jesus cried out, ''My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?'' The centurion confessed Jesus as God''s Son when he saw how he died. Golgotha is translated ''Place of a Skull.'' The exchange between Jesus and Barabbas highlights the injustice of the trial and the substitutionary pattern of the passion. The torn veil marks the significance of Jesus'' death in relation to access to God and judgment on the old order. Their taunts about kingship ironically announce Jesus'' true identity. Joseph''s burial of Jesus establishes both dignity and the public location of the tomb. Jesus was offered wine mixed with myrrh, but he did not take it. The soldiers divided Jesus'' garments by casting lots. Mark names these women among those watching from a distance. Joseph rolled a stone against the door of the tomb. These women came to the tomb early on the first day of the week. When the women arrived, they saw that the stone had already been rolled away. Mark says Jesus appeared first to Mary Magdalene. The messenger at the tomb said Jesus was going before them to Galilee. The women saw a young man in a white robe sitting on the right side inside the tomb. The messenger announced the resurrection and pointed to the empty place where Jesus had been laid. Jesus rebuked the eleven because they did not believe those who had seen him risen. Jesus commissioned the disciples to preach the gospel to all creation. Mark records their fear and trembling after hearing the resurrection message. Mark says Jesus appeared in another form to two of them as they walked into the country. Jesus linked salvation with belief and baptism while condemning unbelief. Mark concludes with Jesus'' ascension and exaltation at God''s right hand. The specific mention of Peter carries grace toward the one who had failed so publicly. Jesus confronts their unbelief and calls them into responsive trust before sending them out. The signs are presented as accompanying believers and confirming the message proclaimed. Sitting at God''s right hand signifies Jesus'' exalted reign and authority. On the way, the women wondered who would roll away the heavy stone from the tomb entrance. Mark notes that Jesus had cast seven demons out of Mary Magdalene. Mark says the disciples did not believe Mary''s report at first. Mark closes by saying the Lord worked with the disciples and confirmed the word through accompanying signs. When Jesus touched the leper, uncleanness did not spread to him; instead, cleansing flowed from him to the leper. Mark opens with John as the forerunner, then presents Jesus as the promised one whose authority and mission fulfill that preparation. Mark 1 joins proclamation and exorcism to show that Jesus announces God''s Kingdom and demonstrates its authority over evil.'
